{"key":"processedPost-9827911","value":{"id":9827911,"first":9825953,"last":9828198,"when":1235088990,"utime":"02/20/09 02:16 AM","cleanedPost":"100% humidity does not cause water droplets to form on the fruits.&nbsp; Having 100% humidity and THEN adding more moisture causes water droplets to form on fruits and every thing else.<br />A bit of moisture after misting is fine, but you don't want to have water just sitting on the fruits and not going anywhere.&nbsp; That's where air exchange comes in.&nbsp; You want constant fresh air, thus there is also a constant loss of moisture from the substrate.&nbsp; This will cause any water droplets on the fruits to evaporate off.&nbsp; Let the substrate dry out for a few hours, and then mist again.&nbsp; This ebb and flow of moisture content is a major pinning trigger.<br />RR"}}